orism in Boston a few months prior to the attacks, thus found herself in a unique position to observe the formation of an immensely important area of government practice. Under Construction goes behind the headlines and beyond official policy to describe the human activities, emotions, relationships, and decisions that shaped the way most Americans experienced homeland security. Fosher’s two years of fieldwork focused on how responders and planners actually worked, illuminating the unofficial strategies that allowed them to resolve conflicts and get things done in the absence of a functioning bureaucracy. Given her unprecedented access, Fosher’s account is an exceptional opportunity to see how seemingly monolithic institutions are constructed, maintained, and potentially transformed by a community of people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivil defensexGovernment policyzMassachusettszBoston Metropolitan Area. 0aCivil defensexGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aLocal governmentzMassachusettszBoston Metropolitan Area. 0aNational securityzUnited States. 0aTerrorismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTerrorismzUnited StatesxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aterrorism, homeland security, counterterrorism, government, 9/11, boston, massachusetts, prevention, policy, nonfiction, politics, administration, national defense, ethics, anthropology, sociology, criminal justice, political science, bureaucracy, ethnography, history, patriot act, tsa, coast guard, border control, secrecy, surveillance, public health, bioterrorism, first responders.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022625743340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226257457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/i